<p>
  Nerves before speaking in front of people you love are not a sign that something is wrong. If
  anything, they're a sign the moment matters to you. That said, there are real, practical things
  you can do in the days and minutes before you speak that make a genuine difference.
</p>

<h2>Know your material differently than you think you do</h2>
<p>
  Most speaking anxiety isn't really about public speaking — it's about the fear of losing your
  place. The fix isn't memorizing word-for-word (which adds pressure), but knowing your structure
  well enough that you could describe what comes next even if you forgot the exact phrasing. Learn
  the shape of your speech, not just the script.
</p>

<h2>Practice out loud, standing up, more than once</h2>
<p>
  Reading silently and speaking aloud use different parts of your brain. The first time you say
  your words out loud shouldn't be in front of the room. Practice standing, at the pace and volume
  you'd actually use, ideally more than once and on more than one day — your comfort with the
  material compounds each time.
</p>

<h2>Have a plan for your hands and your notes</h2>
<p>
  A surprising amount of speaking anxiety is really just not knowing what to do with your hands, or
  fumbling with a card at the wrong moment. Decide in advance: will you hold notes, and if so, on
  what — an index card, a folded page, your phone? Whatever you choose, practice with that exact
  object so it feels familiar rather than foreign in the moment.
</p>

<h2>Use your breath, specifically</h2>
<p>
  "Take a deep breath" is common advice because it works, but the specifics matter. Try a slow
  four-count inhale, a brief hold, and a longer six-count exhale, done two or three times right
  before you're introduced. The longer exhale is what actually signals your nervous system to calm
  down — a quick gasp of air doesn't have the same effect.
</p>
<blockquote>
  You already have the feelings. We simply help you express them.
</blockquote>

<h2>Have an opening line you don't have to think about</h2>
<p>
  The first ten seconds are usually the hardest. If your opening line is fully automatic — something
  you've said aloud enough times that it comes out without thinking — it gets you moving, and
  momentum carries you through the rest more easily than starting cold.
</p>

<h2>Remember who's actually in the room</h2>
<p>
  It's easy to picture a speech as a performance in front of an audience. It helps to remember that
  most people in that room are on your side, want you to succeed, and are far more focused on the
  person or couple being celebrated than on judging your delivery. Nerves tend to imagine a much
  more critical room than the one that's actually there.
</p>
